-------> Scripture

Let's get into scripture

We are currently moving through what is perhaps the most famous sermon ever given - sermon on the mount

It was given by Jesus in front of thousands of people who to came to listen to him speak

The account we're reading of this sermon is written in the gospel of Matthew. Matthew is one of the 4 gospels in the new testament of the bible

Matthew was an outcast jew who abandoned his life as a tax collector for rome to become one of Jesus' 12 apostles

The 12 apostles were Jesus' closest students who spent time with him and served as eyewitnesses to Jesus' teachings and interactions over the course of his ministry

Matthews account of sermon on the mount is the most detailed account. It spans 111 verses, around 2400 words and takes around 15 minutes to read end to end 


Up to this point in sermon on the mount, we've covered Kingdom character with the beatitudes in verses 2-12 

In the beatitudes, Jesus proclaims blessings on those who are poor in spirit (poor in spirit meaning those who acknowledge their need for God

Blessings to those who mourn our sinful world

Blessings to the meek who are gentle, patient and restrain their power

Blessings to those who hunger and thirst for righteousness

Blessings to those who are merciful and pure in heart

Blessings to the peacemakers and those who are persecuted for righteousness sake

And blessings to are those who are persecuted falsely on Jesus' account

To be blessed means to experience deep joy and to receive favour from God


After Kingdom character came Kingdom identity - Christians being the salt of the earth that preserves goodness and light the light of the earth that shine in the darkness of our earthly world

After identity comes kingdom rules with the law

Then Jesus talks about Kingdom behaviours starting with anger and lust 

Jesus then speaks about divorce which we covered last week and that brings us to where we are now at verse 33


--> Read verses 33-37

So the topic in this section is oaths and the words relate to the concepts of honesty and integrity

A oath back then was something that involved Gods name, or a substitute for it, to guarantee the truth of one's statements

Jesus is telling his followers that they should be so honest that their words can be believed without requiring an oath





Summary

At the time, people were invoking Gods name and other things to guarantee the truth of their words

Jesus is telling people to be true to their word so there is no requirement for an oath

Jesus is telling his followers to be honest and have integrity

To mean yes when they say yes, to mean no when they say no

In our house we have a rule to always keep our promises

Trust is built on our reputation for keeping our word

I strive to never make promises I'm not certain I can make good on



